<br>
So I'd divide this discussion up into the &quot;does god prevent free will&quot; topic and the &quot;in the absence of god, is there free will.&quot;<br>
<br>
I don't think the concept of God prevents free will.  It's the assumption that god &quot;built a clock&quot; that causes us to think this way.  He (he for tradition's sake) could have just as easily decided to first create a perfectly random die and then thrown it.  If it came up 6, he'd create the world in 7 days.  But if it came up 3, he'd do it in 5...  He could have defined parameters that he would &quot;not touch&quot;.  It goes back to the old argument if god is good, all powerful, and all knowing why does he let suffering happen.  It's possible for god to limit his own powers, no?  I mean.. he is god afterall.<br>
<br>
And even if he's all knowing and created a perfect clock, we know that there is true randomness at the quantum level.  Maybe that's where god decided to throw the dice.<br>
<br>
Speaking of quantum, book I liked quite a bit called Shadows of the Mind by Roger Penrose poses the theory that conciousness is a super position of quantum particles in the microtubular structure of the brain.  Since quantum is at its core random and TRULY random, not just seemingly random (at least that's the current take) free will is a very real possibility if you believe Penrose.<br>
<br>
The other problem is our language for describing these things.  Given that paradox does exist in our language, it's possible the concept of god is riddled with paradox which gives a concept like free will quite a bit of wiggle room.  It doesn't make the concept wrong, however.  Just unknowable.  For example, &quot;This sentence is false&quot;.  Great paradox.  It's unknowable.  Same as &quot;Can god make a rock he cannot move.&quot;   Unknowable.  <br>
<br>
A Christian would tell you we can know god and his goodness, and the nature of god, but we cannot understand him completely (hence suffering in the world).  Traditional Christianity also believes strongly in the concept of free will.  It's the basis for determination of fate (the free will to choose Christ as savior).<br>
<br>
Speaking of free will.  I'm going to stop typing now <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
